      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>The final step in an attempted synthesis of laurene, a hydrocarbon isolated from the marine alga <i>Laurencia glandulifera,</i> involved the Wittig reaction shown. The product obtained, however, was not laurene but an isomer. Propose a mechanism to account for the unexpected results.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBaGdZIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--66eab908e5c8de42c0a93664833857e805ca3ee0/OChem_22_EC_026.jpg\" alt=\"A substituted cyclopentanone reacts with the Wittig reagent P P h 3- C H 2 in T H F to yield a product, but the expected product Laurene is not formed.\">",
